Additionally, bulk chlorine deliveries come at a discounted rate, reducing operating costs. The return on investment (ROI) for the bulk tank is estimated to be approximately two years.

Name: Co2 Tank comment
Description: The CO2 tank procedure is used to clear underground obstructions within the plumbing by injecting pressurized CO2 through specialized fittings. This process is important because it helps maintain clear and efficient drainage systems, preventing potential backups and costly repairs. Regular use of this procedure is necessary to ensure optimal functionality of the plumbing, reduce maintenance issues, and extend the lifespan of the system, ultimately enhancing the safety and reliability of the facility's operations.

Name: Comment 3-phase Electrical Conversion
Description:
The sub-panel in the equipment room currently receives three-phase power, and the proposal includes converting the existing single-phase motors to three-phase motors. This conversion is recommended for enhanced efficiency, as three-phase motors are inherently more energy-efficient than single-phase motors under the same load. Three-phase motors can turn the same volume of water at a lower pump speed, reducing friction and energy consumption. Additionally, they have a lower upfront cost, as they do not require capacitors, and they draw a steady, constant power stream, leading to more stable and reduced energy usage.

For comparison, think of a single-cylinder engine versus a three-cylinder enginethree-phase motors operate with higher efficiency, typically within a 75% to 95% range. The proposed work includes replacing breakers, installing contactors and a contactor box, replacing corroded timeclocks, and updating the wiring, conduit, plugs, and covers. Converting the motors from single-phase to three-phase will optimize the systems energy efficiency, reduce operating costs, and ensure a robust and reliable setup aligned with the facility's three-phase power supply.

Name: Comment Equipment Room Ventilation
Description: The proposal is to install a ventilation fan in the equipment room to ensure the heaters receive proper airflow, as they require an appropriate gas-to-air ratio for optimal operation. We will install a wall-mounted, high-speed commercial-grade fan that will efficiently exhaust air from the room. This fan will also help vent any corrosive fumes from the chemicals stored in the area, thereby prolonging the longevity of the equipment. To further enhance safety, we have taken proactive steps by installing fume suppressor plugs to reduce the release of chlorine and acid fumes from the containers. The ventilation fan will push fumes out while pulling in fresh air, and we recommend this solution for every equipment room to maintain a safe and efficient environment.

Name: Comment Heater Venting Replacement
Description:
The heater venting has been reported as rusted. The proposal is to replace the damaged and rusted venting to ensure safe operations. Improper ventilation can lead to internal damage to the heaters due to recirculating contaminated air. Heaters require a specific gas-to-air ratio during operation, and rusted venting increases the risk of the pipes developing holes, which could leak flue gases into the equipment area, creating hazardous conditions.

Carbon monoxide (CO) is particularly concerning, as it is a colorless, odorless, tasteless, and non-irritating gas that can be lethal, often referred to as the silent killer. If early signs of CO poisoning, such as fatigue, headaches, confusion, and dizziness, are ignored, individuals may lose consciousness and be unable to escape the danger. CO binds to hemoglobin in the blood, reducing its ability to carry oxygen, which interferes with oxygen delivery to the body's organs.

This repair is necessary to ensure that the heaters operate properly according to the manufacturer's recommendations, thereby safeguarding the health and safety of all users. Addressing the venting issue promptly will help prevent potential hazards and ensure effective heater performance.

Name: Comment Pool Tile Cleaning/Calcium Removal
Description:
The proposal includes performing a comprehensive calcium removal service along the waterline tiles of pool. Over time, calcium and mineral deposits accumulate at the waterline as a result of evaporation and chemical fluctuations in the water. This leads to the formation of hard, white scale along tile surfaces and around metal fixtures such as handrails. If not addressed, these deposits can etch or stain the tile surface, degrade grout, and compromise the appearance and longevity of the finish.

To carry out this service properly, the water level will be lowered approximately 612 inches below the skimmers to fully expose the affected tile areas and allow unobstructed access. Industry-approved techniques such as low-pressure media blasting or the use of safe, specialized descaling solutions will be employed to remove calcium buildup without damaging the tile or surrounding finishes. The handrails at the waterline will also be cleaned to eliminate scale accumulation.

After the removal process, the area will be thoroughly vacuumed to eliminate loose debris, and a commercial-grade tile sealant will be applied to the cleaned surfaces. This sealant creates a protective barrier to help prevent future mineral buildup, enhance resistance to staining, and make routine maintenance easier and more effective. Once sealed, the pool area must remain closed for a full 24-hour curing period to ensure the sealant sets properly.

Following the cure time, the pool will be refilled to the proper level, water chemistry will be tested and rebalanced, and the pool area will be reopened for use. This thorough and proactive service is essential for preserving the aesthetic and structural integrity of the pool area, ensuring it remains clean, visually appealing, and safe for residents and guests. Regular maintenance of this type helps extend the life of the finishes and supports compliance with community presentation standards.

This investment not only keeps you in compliance with health department regulations but also enhances the appearance of your pool area with a high-quality, professional look.

Name: Drain Fountain
Description:
Drain fountain procedure:
First, we drain the body safely without harming any of the equipment. Then, we clear any debris, dirt, or scum found in the body. After, we refill the water to the proper levels. Finally, we rebalance the water chemistry, and ensure it is within proper ranges per health code requirement.

Name: Drain Pool and sand

Name: Drain pool glass removal
Description:
REMOVING THE GLASS VIA DRAINING
First, We close the pool or spa immediately to patrons. Before draining any body of water, We need to address the local water table to ensure that the shell will not succumb to hydrostatic pressure. (NOTE YOUR INSURANCE COMPANY OR BREAKPOINT MAY NEED YOU TO SIGN A RELEASE WAVER RELEASING THEM/US FROM LIABILITY WE VERY RARELEY RECOMEND DRAINING POOLS.)

We turn off Pool Circulation system off. 

Drain The Water using a sump pump rather than the main drain so that none of the water enters the pools circulation system. For a spa, the volume of water is likely so small that it is much more efficient and cost effective to drain the spa. 

Let Everything Dry. If we draining the body of water we wait until it completely dries out. Puddles on the floor can hide the glass shards and prevent proper removal.

We do a thorough sweep multiple times to make sure we get all of the larger glass shards up. 

Once the major shards are swept up, its time to get all of the small slivers with a shop vac. We use a uniform system when vacuuming the pool so we dont miss anything. Once completely swept and vacuumed, We start refilling the water, balancing its chemistry, and opening.

Name: Drain Pool Procedure
Description:
Drain Pool Procedure:
The draining process begins with safely removing the water from the body while ensuring that no equipment is damaged or exposed to unnecessary stress. Once fully drained, the pool is refilled to the appropriate water level, ensuring it reaches halfway up the tile line for proper circulation and skimming efficiency. After refilling, the water chemistry is rebalanced, adjusting chlorine, pH, alkalinity, and other essential levels to meet health code requirements. This procedure is essential for maintaining safe and clean water, preventing equipment strain, and ensuring the body remains compliant with operational standards.

It includes an 11.5-inch stainless steel bowl equipped with a pair of spray heads, both protected by flip-top plastic covers to keep them free from debris. Name: DE Filter Cleaning Large
Description:
DE Filter Cleaning Procedure:
To maintain the efficiency and functionality of the diatomaceous earth (DE) filter, we will remove the cartridges or grids, thoroughly pressure-wash them to eliminate built-up debris, oils, and residual DE powder, and then reassemble the filter. Once the components are cleaned and securely reinstalled, fresh DE powder will be added to coat the grids, enabling the filter to effectively trap fine particles and maintain water clarity. This process is essential for restoring the filters efficiency, reducing system pressure, and ensuring proper water circulation. Regular maintenance of the DE filter prevents poor water quality, minimizes strain on the pump, and extends the lifespan of the filter components. By performing this service, the pool will remain compliant with health and safety regulations, providing clear, safe, and healthy water for users.

Name: Heater Bypass Comment
Description:
We currently have no way of measuring the flow rate going into each pool heater, which is crucial for ensuring they operate properly according to the manufacturer's recommendations. As heaters age, they become increasingly sensitive to flow, leading to error codes that can halt operations.

The proposal is to install a FlowVis and bypass for each heater, along with additional plumbing to restore system functionality. This repair is necessary to prevent more costly issues down the line. Excessive flow can strip the copper in the heat exchanger, while insufficient flow can cause excessive soot buildup, leading to premature heater failure. Implementing this solution will help maintain optimal performance and extend the lifespan of the equipment.

Name: Heater Venting Missing/Absent Comment
Description:
The heater venting has been reported as absent, significantly increasing the risk of internal damage to the heaters due to recirculating contaminated air. Heaters require a specific gas-to-air ratio during operation, and the lack of proper venting can lead to hazardous conditions, including elevated carbon monoxide (CO) levels in the room. Carbon monoxide is a colorless, odorless, tasteless, and non-irritating gas that can be lethal, often referred to as the silent killer. If early signs of CO poisoning, such as fatigue, headaches, confusion, and dizziness, are ignored, individuals may lose consciousness and be unable to escape the danger. CO binds to hemoglobin in the blood, reducing its ability to carry oxygen, which interferes with oxygen delivery to the bodys organs.

The proposal is to deliver and install proper venting for the heater to ensure safe operations. This repair is essential for compliance with the manufacturer's recommendations and to safeguard the health and safety of all users. Implementing this solution will help prevent potential hazards and ensure the heaters operate effectively.

Name: Invoice Repair Comment
Description: Repairs and part replacements were completed promptly to maintain safe and uninterrupted operation of the pool and surrounding area. These minor corrective actions were performed under our standing maintenance agreement, which authorizes repairs below the $500 threshold to address health, safety, and operational concerns. All work was performed in accordance with California Code of Regulations Title 22, Title 24, and Title 20, as well as NEC Article 680, NFPA 54, ANSI/NSF 50, DOE energy efficiency requirements, ADA accessibility standards, and VGB pool and spa safety provisions to ensure proper, lawful, and safe operation of the facility.

Name: IPS Comment
Description:
The body of water currently lacks an automatic system to detect chemical deficiencies and inject necessary sanitizing chemicals. We must rely on anticipating future usage and consumption rates while manually adjusting slow-erosion and slow-feed chemical feeders, which is nearly impossible to maintain throughout the day in smaller bodies of water. Furthermore, recent tightening of chemical parameters set by the Department of Health has led to closures at accounts without chemical controllers across the Inland Empire.

To achieve a more consistent chemical balance, we propose installing chemical controllers (IPS M920ca) that can detect imbalances and automatically inject required chemicals, such as chlorine or acid. These controllers maintain safe and accurate chemical levels within the water, helping to preserve equipment and plaster, maintain water quality, and ensure the safety of bathers. They can reduce chemical costs by up to 30%, effectively paying for themselves within five years.

The price includes the chemical controller, ORP and pH probes, flow cell, flow switch, and mounting board. With many years of experience using these controllers, we are confident in their reliability and longevity. They come with a five-year factory warranty on electronics and a one-year warranty on the chemical probes, flow cell, and flow switch, along with local factory support. These Wi-Fi-enabled controllers can comply with the new "every day" testing mandates from the Department of Environmental Health as outlined in Title 22, Chapter 20, Section 65523. They can check chemical parameters as required by Health Department authorities, log data, and alert the pool service company of any irregularities.

Name: IPS Interlocking Comment
Description: IPS controllers must be interlocked according to the manufacturers recommendations to prevent chemical feeding when the equipment is shut off, which can lead to hazardous conditions. Completing this repair will ensure that the chemical pumps comply with California Code Regulations Title 24, Section 3133B.3. This important safety measure will help maintain a safe environment while ensuring the proper functioning of the chemical systems.

Name: Leak detection procedure
Description:
Leak detection procedure:
We apply different leak detection tests on the body of water to find where the loss of water for the body is going. These tests include a liquid test, evaporative test, and a pressure test. Once concluded where the leaks are coming from, we aim to repair if possible or we standby for an approval. Priced per body of water.

This protective enclosure will help ensure that the life ring remains accessible and in good condition, enhancing safety for all pool users.

Name: Light J&J Warranty Comment
Description: PureWhite LED Light Fixtures are rated for up to 50,000 hours of use, significantly reducing long-term maintenance costs. Additionally, all PureWhite LED Light Fixtures come with an industry-leading three-year limited warranty, ensuring reliability and peace of mind for your lighting needs.

Name: Mastic Comment
Description:
This proposal includes the removal and replacement of the deteriorated mastic (Deck-O-Seal) located in the immediate expansion joints surrounding the bodies of water on site. The existing rubberized sealant in these areas has begun to crack and separate, compromising its ability to accommodate normal expansion and contraction between the pool shell and surrounding decking. Maintaining a watertight seal at these critical joints is essential to prevent water intrusion beneath the deck, which can lead to subgrade erosion, deck movement, or structural damage to the bodies.

The scope of work includes removing the existing mastic, cleaning and preparing the expansion joints, and applying new grey rubberized mastic with a light sand finish for a clean, grouted appearance unless otherwise specified.

Please note that this proposal specifically addresses only the mastic immediately bordering the pool, spa, or other water features. Radiating or decorative deck joints outside these areas are typically aesthetic in nature and not included in this scope. If desired, a separate estimate can be provided to address those additional joints.

This work ensures the functional integrity of the waterline expansion joints while maintaining compliance with standard pool construction and maintenance practices. A one-year manufacturers warranty applies to any defective product following installation.

Name: On-Deck Depth Marker Tile Replacement Comment
Description: We propose to replace the on-deck six-inch square numbered depth marker. These black numbered depth markers with a white background are required by state and local codes to be in good repair and legible. The process will involve breaking up the existing tile, jackhammering out the old tile, and securely installing and grouting the new six-inch numbered tile. This replacement is essential to maintain compliance with safety regulations and ensure the markers are clear and visible for all pool users.

Name: Refill Valve Comment
Description: Due to failure, we need to replace the existing system with a commercial-grade anti-backflow refill valve that includes a solenoid and an actuator. This installation will facilitate the automatic daily refill of water back into the pool and spa as needed, ensuring consistent water levels and compliance with safety standards. This upgrade will enhance efficiency and reliability in maintaining the water supply.

Name: Replaster/Resurface comment
Description:
Replaster Procedure:
The proposal is to perform a replaster procedure for the pool body. This process will involve removing the existing plaster while carefully preserving the current waterline tile. We will add trim and install new code-compliant drain covers, which includes covering all necessary fees to the county. Finally, we will apply a durable quartz plaster finish to enhance both aesthetics and longevity. This comprehensive approach ensures the pool meets safety standards and provides a refreshed look.

Name: Sand filter rejuvenation recharge
Description: Perform the sand filter rejuvenation procedure due to unresponsive and cloudy water, or after major wind storm clean-up. Sand filters must have the internal sand rejuvenated periodically. How often depends on the amount of dirt blown in by windstorms, bathe load, water clarity, and how quickly the filter loads up again after backwashing, otherwise known as "short-cycling".  This procedure is done only after encountering cloudy water or short-cycling sand filters, perhaps once or twice a year depending on usage or wind. This procedure results in superior water quality, eliminates much more expensive sand replacement procedures, and is the hallmark of our success in commercial swimming pool maintenance.

Name: Track Drain Service
Description:
Track Drain Service- Priced per Linear Foot

This proposal covers the removal, cleaning, and reinstallation of the track drains surrounding the pool deck. The scope of work includes removing accumulated debris, dirt, and organic matter from within the drain channels to ensure proper water flow and drainage. Our technicians will inspect grates and drain lines for blockages, flush the channels as needed, and restore clear flow throughout the system. Regular maintenance of track drains helps prevent flooding on the pool deck, reduces slip hazards, and extends the service life of the drainage system.

Name: Skimmer Replacement Comment
Description: The replacement of the existing skimmer is a crucial maintenance task that ensures the proper functioning and longevity of the pool system. A damaged or outdated skimmer can lead to inefficiencies in water circulation, affecting water quality and clarity. Additionally, broken pipes can result in leaks, which may compromise the structural integrity of the pool and lead to costly repairs down the line. By saw-cutting the concrete deck and properly installing a new Waterway skimmer, we are not only repairing existing issues but also preventing potential future problems. Proper compaction and blending of the new concrete ensure a seamless integration with the surrounding deck, maintaining the pool's aesthetic appeal. Re-grouting the tile around the skimmer opening further enhances the installation's durability and prevents debris accumulation. This replacement is essential for maintaining optimal water circulation, ensuring a safe swimming environment, and protecting the investment in the pool.

Name: Soda-blast Pool Beach Entryway
Description:
High Pressure Soda Blast Tile and Grout at Beach Entry Swimming Pool:
 We regularly brush the swimming pool beach entryway and do periodic hand cleaning with cleaning agents however, a soda blasting process is now required to remove dark discoloration and buildup.  We use soda bicarbonate as the blasting medium to preserve the tile glaze and grout integrity.  We recommend this be done to all beach entry pools at a minimum of twice a year and should be budgeted for.

Name: Solar inspection
Description:
Solar inspection:
Performed diagnosis of the existing solar pool heater system, including a pressure test, and the inspection of plumbing, valves, control unit, sensors, collectors, and connections. The site was visited and serviced. We found 36 (4x12) FAFCO collector panels, installed on 1-story slate tile roof with metal rack. The technicians found and remounted the slipping panels. We tightened all the rubber hose clamps, and replaced the malfunctioning Pentair water sensor. The equipment was pressure tested and no leaks were found. The equipment was left in good working order.

Name: Splash Park Bead-Blast.
Description:
*Splash Park Spray Features Restoration:  

The multi-colored Splash Park upright  spray features at the pool area were faded and encrusted with calcium deposits.  

A Bead-blasting procedure on the pool area water splash park multi-colored spray/splash features was performed.
Calcium was removed from the splash park painted features utilizing glass or walnut beads and a low air pressure to safely preserve the integrity of the paint.
A protective clear-coat agent was applied over the painted surfaces after the procedure to protect paint and prevent further calcium deposits from forming. 
This purpose of this procedure is to preserve and protect the original factory paint.
A protective T-2 polymer clear-coat sealer (same as Disneyland uses)  is applied over the painted surfaces after the procedure to make it shine, protect paint and prevent further calcium deposits from forming.

Name: Splash Park Spray Feature Restoration
Description:
Splash Park Spray Features Restoration:

The multi-colored Splash Park spray features at the poolside splash pad have become faded and stained with calcium deposits.  

Restoration to these upright features will consist of sanding off the calcium deposits, properly preparing (including spot priming) and applying a single coat of polyurethane paint to all multi-colored spray features to restore them to their original colors and shine.  This polyurethane paint is water and sun resistant, holds its color and adhesiveness for many years and we have had great success with this process.

Name: Start-up Spa
Description:
Spa start-up procedure:
The spa start-up after replastering is a 10-day procedure that begins with raising the alkalinity immediately upon refilling the water. Next, we vacuum the plaster surfaces using a brush vac head only. After that, we add stain and scale inhibitors based on the volume of water, along with cyanuric acid. We also recharge sand filters and perform a complete tear down and cleaning of diatomaceous earth filters. To maintain the quality of the plaster surfaces, we brush and/or vacuum them daily for the duration of the 10 days. This thorough process ensures optimal conditions for the newly plastered spa.

Name: Comment Fountain Tile Cleaning Mineral Blast Comment
Description:
Proposal submitted for fountain mineral blast procedures. Over time, calcium and mineral deposits naturally accumulate along the tile surfaces of water features due to evaporation and fluctuations in water chemistry. These deposits form hard, white scale that can etch or stain tile surfaces, deteriorate grout, and diminish the overall appearance and lifespan of the finish if not properly maintained.

To address this, the water level will be lowered as needed to fully expose the affected tile areas, allowing safe and unobstructed access for cleaning. Industry-approved low-pressure media blasting and/or specialized descaling solutions will be used to remove calcium buildup effectively without damaging the tile or adjacent finishes. Any exposed waterline surfaces will also be cleaned to remove accumulated mineral scale.

Upon completion, all debris will be vacuumed and removed from the fountain basins. A commercial-grade tile sealant will then be applied to protect the cleaned surfaces, reducing future mineral buildup, improving stain resistance, and simplifying ongoing maintenance. The fountain will remain closed for a minimum 24-hour curing period to ensure the sealant sets properly before refilling and returning the feature to normal operation.

This preventive service enhances both the appearance and longevity of the fountain finishes while supporting community presentation standards and maintaining safe, attractive amenities for residents and guests.

Name: Pentair 2 HP, 1-Phase, TEFC replacement

Our service includes removal of the existing motor, installation of the new Pentair unit, inspection of the pump assembly, alignment of all components, and verification of correct operation upon completion. Installing this upgraded TEFC motor will provide improved durability, energy efficiency, and reduced risk of system downtime for the property.

Name: 2.25 THP VS VGreen Motor replacement Comment
